When I moved to Newark, New Jersey 20 years ago from law school to help low-income families take on slumlords, I saw a community I thought was defined by its problems—gun violence, mass incarceration, generations of poverty.   But it was a leader in that community, Ms. Virginia Jones, one of my first mentors, who showed me: if all you see are the problems, that is all there is ever going to be. If you want to make a difference, you have to have a defiant vision of what’s possible.   I’m running for president because I believe that if we come together, we can accomplish things others say are impossible.  It’s how we organized to beat those slumlords in Newark, it’s how we turned Newark around after generations of decline, and how I brought people together to pass criminal justice reform under a Republican president and Senate.   At a time when we have a president who is trying to divide us and problems that feel impossible to solve, it is more important than ever to remember that the way we’ve won every fight for justice in our history is by uniting in common purpose. My mom has been a source of deep wisdom throughout my life.  When I was growing up, she tried to instill in my brother and me this understanding: don’t forget why you’re here, don’t forget what it took. Don’t forget the values and the work that got you here.  Well, I know I’ll never forget the values she instilled in me and the work she did to get me where I am today -- from her inspiring activism during the civil rights movement to the hard work and dose of grace that led to her becoming one of the earliest African American executives at IBM.  So on this first day of Women’s History Month, I wanted to take a minute to honor my mom and all of the other amazing women who make us better, make our country better. And as we celebrate their incredible legacy, we must also recognize the injustices women continue to face today -- from the gender pay gap to attacks on women’s health as recently as this week in Congress. And we must redouble our efforts to create a more fair and equal society.
Our fight for a more just and fair America demands the courage to confront the most difficult moments in our history.

text: A note from Cleo on my fridge at home in Newark, complete with a magnet from Glass Roots, a nonprofit that teaches glass blowing and more (check'em out). Fear is toxic. Watching it used in politics angers me. Great presidents and states-people of the past called upon us as a nation - often in our most difficult and uncertain times - NOT to be led by our fears but by our courage. "We have nothing to fear but fear itself"  Beware of leaders who sell, exaggerate, or inspire fear.  And in my life, I have found that the most dangerous voice of fear isn't from demagogues, or bigoted bloviators. The worst most toxic voice of fear are those voices we all face within.  The internal voices that can pick up the toxic talk around us and echo it within; the voices that tell us not to try;  the voices that tell us not to risk extending a hand, speaking up, or giving to another; The internal voices that try to make us believe life is a zero sum, dog eat dog, scarcity world.  No, we are and the world is so much larger than that.  Whether the talk comes from a voice on the evening news, or one inside may we remember that:  Fear fractures. Love expands  Fear limits. Love expands.  Fear is small. Love expands.  Fear diminishes power. Love expands it.  Fear kills dreams. Love expands them.  I believe in the limitless possibilities of individuals. When we confront fear, conquer it, and approach life with a defiant faith and courageous empathy we expand life and life's possibilities.  That is also the story of this nation as well. We are not small, our dream, our promise can not be undercut by small minds or fear peddling hucksters.  Our generosity to Europe after the war (The Marshall Plan), the courage of black, white, Jewish, Christian Americans who loved so fearlessly they faced death together (Goodman, Cheney and Schwerner fighting for voting rights in Mississippi), our nation is replete with heroic tales of those who led with faith and love, not fear.  I am an imperfect exponent of such values. But perhaps a courageous ideal is just getting up everyday - despite our hurt, pain and fears - and trying again, to lead with love and more faithfully face the world.From my local assemblyman,  Hal Wirths.  To the pink hat Democrats, the answers should be there, but they aren't.  Why?  You only matter as much to Democrats...
"History, despite its wrenching pain, cannot be unlived, but if faced with courage, need not be lived again." Maya Angelou

You may write me down in history With your bitter, twisted lies, You may trod me in the very dirt But still, like dust, I'll rise.  Does my sassiness upset you? Why are you beset with gloom? 'Cause I walk like I've got oil wells Pumping in my living room.  Just like moons and like suns, With the certainty of tides, Just like hopes springing high, Still I'll rise.  Did you want to see me broken? Bowed head and lowered eyes? Shoulders falling down like teardrops, Weakened by my soulful cries?  Does my haughtiness offend you? Don't you take it awful hard 'Cause I laugh like I've got gold mines Diggin' in my own backyard.  You may shoot me with your words, You may cut me with your eyes, You may kill me with your hatefulness, But still, like air, I'll rise.  Does my sexiness upset you? Does it come as a surprise That I dance like I've got diamonds At the meeting of my thighs?  Out of the huts of history's shame I rise Up from a past that's rooted in pain I rise I'm a black ocean, leaping and wide, Welling and swelling I bear in the tide.  Leaving behind nights of terror and fear I rise Into a daybreak that's wondrously clear I rise Bringing the gifts that my ancestors gave, I am the dream and the hope of the slave. I rise I rise I rise.  Maya Angelou
